<author><name><![CDATA[JoelHickman]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-11-17T23:06:26+00:00</updated>
<id>https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=145&amp;p=5392#p5392</id>
<link href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=145&amp;p=5392#p5392"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[There are many useful frame attributes that seem ignored]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=145&amp;p=5392#p5392"><![CDATA[
Unless I am mistaken, the implicit assumption is that all of the pages are on one server.  For me, at least, this is not the case ( <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.csun.edu/~instrsch/">http://www.csun.edu/~instrsch/</a><!-- m --> ).  I use templates in the main university server so that content providers may update static pages with tools like contribute.  On this server, I have few  permissions.  On a server owned by our department, we run a Tomcat servlet container, and are able to host dynamic database driven applications and reports. Using frames with their state saving properties, I am able to blend these components well, and even institute a page tracking that is able to put all of the userâ€™s actions into one pseudo-session.  <br />I can understand the web-crawling/bookmarking problems posed by frames, and that there is a certain beauty to the notion of having a one URL to site correlation.  On the other hand, if seems to me that many web developers seem to live in a realm where they either have a great deal of control over the hosting machines or host mostly static sites.  <br />I suspect with the adoption of HTML 5, I will find some work around, and I suspect in line frames may be part of that solution.  I also suspect that they will not suffice.  In that case, I may have to build a more complex technical solution that relies on something like EJB to coordinate between the two servers.  Of course, the real complexity will come from politics and intersecting authority/ security spheres of influence of the groups maintaining those servers.  <br />This seems like a lot of trouble to go to in order to maintain the same capabilities I have now just because browser developers were not clever enough to fully support the standards that they had a large hand in bringing about.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=707">JoelHickman</a> — Tue Nov 17, 2009 11:06 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
